[[Antimicrobial peptides]] are short [[Peptide|peptides]] that possess [[antimicrobial]] properties. The female reproductive tract and its tissues produce antimicrobial peptides as part of the [[immune response]]. These peptides are able to fight pathogens and at the same time allow the maintenance of the [[microbiota]] that are part of the [[Female reproductive system|reproductive system in women]].
*[[Defensins]] ** [[Alpha defensin|alpha-Defensins]] ** [[Beta defensin|beta-Defensins]] ** [[Theta defensin|theta-defensins]] * [[Cathelicidin|Cathelicidins]] * [[LL37|LL-37]] * [[Whey Acidic Protein|Whey acid proteins]] * [[SLPI]] * [[Elafin]] * HE-4 * [[Lysozyme]] * [[S100 protein|S100 proteins]] **[[Calprotectin|Calpotectin]] **Psoriasin ([[S100A7]]) * [[C-type lectin|C-type lectins]] **SP-A **SP-D *Iron metabolism proteins **[[Lactoferrin]] * Kinocidins **[[CCL20]]/Mip-3-alpha<ref name="YarbroughWinkle2014">{{cite journal|last1=Yarbrough|first1=V. L.|last2=Winkle|first2=S.|last3=Herbst-Kralovetz|first3=M. M.|title=Antimicrobial peptides in the female reproductive tract: a critical component of the mucosal immune barrier with physiological and clinical implications|journal=Human Reproduction Update|volume=21|issue=3|year=2014|pages=353–377|issn=1355-4786|doi=10.1093/humupd/dmu065|pmid=25547201}}</ref>
