{{Infobox Hospital | Name = Sindh Institute of Urology & Transplantation (SIUT) | Org/Group = Dewan Farooq Medical Complex | Image = | Caption = | Logo = SIUT logo.jpg | Location = Near [[Civil Hospital]] | Region = [[Karachi]] | State = [[Sindh]] | Country = [[Pakistan]] | HealthCare = <!-- UK:NHS. AU/CA: Medicare. ELSE freetext, eg Private --> | Type = Specialist and teaching <!-- Community, District, General, District General, Teaching, Specialist --> | Speciality = [[Nephropathy|Kidney Disease]], [[Urology]], [[Organ transplantation|Transplantation]] | Emergency = Yes | Affiliation= | Beds = 1000 | Founded = 1970 by Prof Dr. Adibul Hasan Rizvi | Closed = <!-- optional --> | Website = http://www.siut.org/ | Wiki-Links = <!-- optional, autofilled [List hospitals in <State>] --> |}}
The '''Sindh Institute of Urology & Transplantation''' ('SIUT')<ref name="DFMC1">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dewangroup.com.pk/about.htm |title=About DMG |accessdate=2010-05-03 |publisher=[[Dewan Mushtaq Group]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221094920/http://www.dewangroup.com.pk/about.htm |archivedate=21 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> is a [[dialysis]] & [[kidney transplant]] centre located in [[Pakistan]].<ref name="dt-19jul2009">{{Cite news |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2009%5C07%5C19%5Cstory_19-7-2009_pg15_2 |title=Interview with Adib Rizvi|last=Shahzad |first=Rabeea |work=[[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] |publisher=Media Times Ltd|accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref>
SIUT was founded by Dr. [[Adibul Hasan Rizvi]] and it is [[Pakistan]]'s largest [[kidney disease]] center,<ref name="SIUT1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.siut.org/histroy.htm |title=Prof Dr. Adibul Hasan Rizvi |accessdate=10 May 2010 |publisher=www.siut.org |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100127182021/http://www.siut.org/histroy.htm |archivedate=27 January 2010 }}</ref> as well as Pakistan's largest public sector health organisation.<ref name="dt-19jul2009"/> It began as a department of [[urology]] at the government-run [[Civil Hospital]] in 1970<ref name="ips-23dec2003"/> and became autonomous in 1991.<ref name="dt-19jul2009"/> 10-12 transplants are performed weekly,<ref name="dt-19jul2009"/> and in 2003 doctors at SIUT performed Pakistan's first liver transplant.<ref name="ips-23dec2003"/> In 2004, a child care unit was opened.<ref name="SIUT3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/2004/02/16/local8.htm |title=KARACHI: Unit for children at SIUT set up |last=Siddiqui |first=Nizamuddin |date=16 February 2004 |accessdate=10 May 2010 |work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |publisher=[[Dawn Group of Newspapers]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040929025017/http://www.dawn.com/2004/02/16/local8.htm |archivedate=29 September 2004 }}</ref>
All services provided by SIUT, including dialysis and transplantation, are provided free of cost.<ref name="dt-19jul2009"/><ref name="ips-23dec2003">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/interna.asp?idnews=21683|title=Debate Reopened on Whether Organ Donations are Islamic|last=Ebrahim|first=Zofeen|work=IPS News|publisher=[[Inter Press Service]]|date=23 December 2003|accessdate=10 May 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071125165915/http://www.ipsnews.net/interna.asp?idnews=21683|archivedate=25 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="SIUT4">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/2009/01/13/local3.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130121160432/http://www.dawn.com/2009/01/13/local3.htm|dead-url=yes|archive-date=21 January 2013|title=KARACHI: Experts back ban on organ ‘donation’ to foreigners|date=13 January 2009|accessdate=10 May 2010|work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=[[Dawn Group of Newspapers]]}} </ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sindhidunya.com/sindh-institute-of-urology-and-transplantation/|title=Sindh Institute of Urology and Transplantation: The Most Reputed Institute of Sindh|date=2017-12-07|work=Sindhi Dunya|access-date=2018-03-28|language=en-US}}</ref>
